description.value: An anklet: composed of beads, an amulet and two pendants. One of the pendants, which is long and resembles an unmarked snake's head amulet,  is of translucent dark sea-green olivine with black flecks; the other pendant is drop-shaped and made of cornelian. Seven of the beads are large, flat, lenticular and oval; two have distinct ridges along their edges. All are made of translucent green calcite or white calcite. A rectangular bead with rounded corners, flat underside and convex upper surface is of malachite. There are twenty disc, short cylindrical and short truncated convex bicone beads: nine are of rock crystal, eight of calcite, two of green fluorite and one of shell. There is one oblate bead of faded green feldspar and one tiny disc bead of the same material. One long barrel is of mottled dark-green steatite, one long cylinder of black steatite and one flattened long cylinder of brown, semi-translucent steatite. The hedgehog amulet is made of calcite. Cornelian barrel and cylindrical disc beads, two much-faceted short truncated convex bicone beads and three semi-circular tabular beads make up the remainder of the anklet.

description.value: Terracotta antefixal ornament decorated with a dramatic mask.  An antefixal ornament in the form of a dramatic mask, possibly tragic, beardless and wearing a low onkos with long straight hair, and with an open mouth; two small bosses at the forehead may be bunches of ivy-berries (which may be evidence against the mask being tragic; Webster, Green and Seeberg 1995 regard it as a youthful mask from the New Comedy). Rising from the top of the mask are two vertical elements in relief, flanked by raised edges, all curving back but now much broken. At the rear, the upper part is concave, below which is the break from the straight tile from which it has come away. The face was pressed into a mould and then applied to the antefix; the lower part is detached at the join. It is not, as a first glance might indicate, a pot-support from a cooking-stove.  Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt with a grey core. The front and sides have a white dressing, and much detail is indicated with paint: the eyes, eyebrows and mouth, the cheeks, and the mask, hair and vertical elements, in black outline, and a black stripe runs along the proper right edge; the eyes, mouth, mask and vertical elements also have red detailing.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta antefix corner. An antefixal ornament from the corner of a structure, with simplified acanthus decoration. It is hand-modelled, with applied leaves, the edges of which are defined by incised grooves. Rough holes are pierced almost right through, below the arch of the lowest leaves on each side, and the stumps of inserted clay stems survive in both. Orange-brown Nile silt with a grey core, with common gold mica and white inclusions.
